findings.recommendation:
Add a ticks > 0 guard before calling formatCPUTime for IODelay, consistent with the existing guard already in buildProcPidResult for rate columns. Example:
  if delayAcctAvailable && validPID && haveCPU && ticks > 0 {
      row[11] = nullString(formatCPUTime(curCPU.IODelay, ticks))
  } else {
      row[11] = nullString("00:00:00")
  }
Alternatively, guard inside formatCPUTime itself: if ticks <= 0 { return "00:00:00" }

Validate that probePID > 1 and is a reasonable PID value (e.g. < 4194304, the Linux default PID_MAX) before passing it to CheckIOAvailable. Example:
  if probePID <= 1 || probePID > 4194304 {
      probePID = 1 // or skip the probe and set ioAvailable = false
  }
This is defense-in-depth; the current fallback to 1 already caps the worst case.

Explicitly add the guard in Task 1 and add a dedicated golden file test with fewer than 40 suffix fields to confirm the error path is returned rather than a panic. The guard should read:
  if len(suffix) < 40 {
      return stat, fmt.Errorf("%s bad content: not enough fields for IODelay in '%s'", statfile, line)
  }
The existing test 'pid_stat_malformed' should be extended or a new file added covering this boundary.
